Original Docket Text: STANDING ORDER IN RE PILOT PROJECT REGARDING CASE MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES FOR COMPLEX CIVIL CASES IN THE SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK (See M-10-468 Order filed November 1, 2011). This case is hereby designated for inclusion in the Pilot Project Regarding Case Management Techniques for Complex Civil Cases in the Southern District of New York (the Pilot Project), unless the judge to whom this case is assigned determines otherwise. This case is designated for inclusion in the Pilot Project because it is a class action, an MDL action, or is in one of the following Nature of Suit categories: 160, 245, 315, 355, 365, 385, 410, 830, 840, 850, 893, or 950. The presiding judge in a case that does not otherwise qualify for inclusion in the Pilot Project may nevertheless designate the case for inclusion in the Pilot Project by issuing an order directing that the case be included in the Pilot Project. The description of the Pilot Project, including procedures to be followed, is attached to this Order. (Signed by Judge Loretta A. Preska on 10/31/2011) (jom) (Entered: 09/25/2013)

IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that any communication regarding any discovery dispute in the New York, Kansas, or California actions, which shall not exceed two-pages in length, shall be submitted concurrently to all judicial officers listed above. IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that, unless otherwise specified (e.g., the two-page limit on discovery disputes), the parties shall file the aforementioned papers in accordance with the individual practices of each judicial officer. Original Docket Text: ORDER...[T]he parties shall continue the meet-and-confer process for the next two weeks and seek to resolve or narrow outstanding disputes as to all issues in all actions. A report shall be due by May 2, 2014. IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that defendant NovaStar shall promptly engage in this meet-and-confer process in a good faith effort to reach agreement with NCUA or to narrow any areas of disagreement by May 2, 2014. IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that the May 2, 2014 submissions shall supersede the April 18, 2014 submissions, and thus need not refer to the April 18 submissions. IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that, pursuant to the April 9, 2014 Master Discovery Protocol, all applications and disputes regarding discovery in these actions will be filed in the lead case pending in the Southern District of New York (currently 13 Civ. 6705). If the application or dispute applies to fewer than all actions, then the submission should be filed as well in the action or actions to which it applies. (Signed by Judge Denise L. Cote, Coordination Judge in these NCUA Actions on 4/22/2014) (gr) Modified on 4/22/2014 (gr). (Entered: 04/22/2014)

Original Docket Text: ORDER: it is hereby ORDERED that, by March 26, Goldman Sachs shall identify to NCUA (1) any CDO lawsuit involving any of the RMBS in these coordinated actions in which Goldman Sachs or one of its officers or employees was a party; (2) the extent to which a Goldman Sachs entity was a sponsor or underwriter of the RMBS in that CDO lawsuit; (3) the identity of any deponents in that CDO lawsuit who is also a custodian in these coordinated actions; and (4) the number of any additional Goldman Sachs deponents in that CDO lawsuit. IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that the parties shall meet and confer with each other following the March 26 disclosure and may bring any remaining dispute to the attention of our Courts by following the procedures in the MDP. (Signed by Judge Denise Cote on 3/19/15) (sr) (Entered: 03/19/2015)

Original Docket Text: ORDER...that, if a motion pertaining to these coordinated actions is made in a court other than our three Courts (such as the motion discussed in NCUAs May 19 letter), the parties implicated by that motion shall convey to the judicial officer to whom the motion is assigned that our Courts stand ready and willing to accept transfer of the motion. The parties shall also convey that a transfer of the motion can be effected by transferring the motion to the Hon. Denise Cote in the Southern District of New York, whereafter it shall be ruled upon following consultation among Judge Cote, Judges Lungstrum and/or OHara, and Judge Wu. IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that promptly after any such transfer the party seeking the discovery shall file in each district in this coordinated litigation copies of the motion papers related to the dispute. IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that the parties shall also convey to the judicial officer to whom such a motion is addressed that, pursuant to the Master Discovery Protocol and a May 13, 2015 Order entered in these coordinated actions, our Courts have mechanisms in place for resolving disputes that arise both in advance of and during a deposition. (Signed by Judge Denise L. Cote (S.D.N.Y.), Judge George H. Wu (C.D. Cal.), Judge John W. Lungstrum (D. Kan.), Magistrate Judge James P. OHara (D. Kan.)on 5/20/2015) (gr) (Entered: 05/20/2015)
Name Portion: Denise Cote Lungstrum OHara Wu Denise L. Cote George H. Wu John W. Lungstrum James P. OHara

Original Docket Text: STANDING ORDER IN RE PILOT PROJECT REGARDING CASE MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES FOR COMPLEX CIVIL CASES IN THE SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK (See M-10-468 Order filed November 1, 2011). This case is hereby designated for inclusion in the Pilot Project Regarding Case Management Techniques for Complex Civil Cases in the Southern District of New York (the Pilot Project), unless the judge to whom this case is assigned determines otherwise. This case is designated for inclusion in the Pilot Project because it is a class action, an MDL action, or is in one of the following Nature of Suit categories: 160, 245, 315, 355, 365, 385, 410, 830, 840, 850, 893, or 950. The presiding judge in a case that does not otherwise qualify for inclusion in the Pilot Project may nevertheless designate the case for inclusion in the Pilot Project by issuing an order directing that the case be included in the Pilot Project. The description of the Pilot Project, including procedures to be followed, is attached to this Order. (Signed by Judge Loretta A. Preska on 10/31/2011) (mro) (Entered: 08/13/2012)

Original Docket Text: ENDORSED LETTER addressed to Magistrate Judge Frank Maas from Stephen L. Ascher dated 3/31/10 re: The parties have agreed to the enclosed Stipulated Confidentiality Agreement and Protective Order ("Order"). Because of thenature of the discovery in this matter, the parties have agreed to certain modifications to Judge Gardephe's Model Stipulated Confidentiality Agreement and Protective Order. These modifications are illustrated in the attached redline comparing the enclosed Order to the court's model order. Please let us know if you have any questions about the parties' enclosed Order, which werespectfully submit for Your Honor's approval. ENDORSEMENT: I am concerned about para. 1 of the proposed order, which, as amended, extends confidentiality to ALL testimony, not just deposition testimony. To my understanding, if confidential information is used during the course of a trial, it loses its prior protection. Either para. 1 needs to be reworded or someone needs to explain to me why my understanding is wrong. (Signed by Magistrate Judge Frank Maas on 3/31/10) (db) (Entered: 04/01/2010)
Name Portion: Frank Maas Stephen L. Ascher Gardephe Frank Maas

Original Docket Text: FOURTH REVISED SCHEDULING ORDER: The parties to this action hereby submit this Fourth Revised Scheduling Order ("Fourth Revised Scheduling Order"). This Fourth Revised Scheduling Order amends the relevant provisions of the Civil) Case Management Plan and Scheduling Order dated February 14, 2011, the Second Revised Scheduling Order dated July 16, 2012 and the Third Revised Scheduling Order dated September 12,2012 as follows: Plaintiffs' expert disclosures are required by Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 26(a)(2) shall be served by November 20, 2012. Defendants' expert disclosures as required by Federal Rule of Civil Procedure 26(a)(2) shall be served by March 1, 2013. Plaintiffs' rebuttal expert reports, if any shall be served by April 19, 2013. All demonstrative exhibits, including those to be used to illustrate the testimony of experts, need not be disclosed at the time expert reports are submitted but shall be disclosed at a time agreed upon by the partied or ordered by the Court.
